  geom_bar(position="dodge") + labs(title='position="dodge"')

#Based on this distribution we will consider Ratings 1,2,3 as negative and Ratings 4,5 as positive.


#Distribution of Star rating with Helpful votes
rating <- aggregate(star_rating,list(star_rating),length)
names(rating)<-c("Stars","Total")

helpful <- aggregate(helpful_votes,list(star_rating),sum)
names(helpful)<-c("Stars","Helpful Reviews")

total_votes_gf <- aggregate(total_votes,list(star_rating),sum)
names(total_votes_gf)<-c("Stars","Total Votes")


#Do this later.
#vine_gf <- aggregate(vine,list(star_rating),sum)
names(total_votes_gf)<-c("Stars","Total Votes")



review_rating_type <- merge(rating,helpful,by= "Stars")
review_rating_type <- merge(review_rating_type,total_votes_gf,by= "Stars")

plot(review_rating_type$Stars,(review_rating_type$`Helpful Reviews`/review_rating_type$Total) *100, type = "b", xlab = "Stars", ylab ="% Helpful Reviews", main = "Relationship between Star Rating and Helpful Votes ", col ="darkblue",lwd=1.5)

#Based on graph, we found that as the star rating increases percentage of helphul votes decreases or reviews with singlw star rating are more helpful than reviews having 5 star rating.


plot(review_rating_type$Stars,(review_rating_type$`Total Votes`/review_rating_type$Total) *100, type = "b", xlab = "Stars", ylab ="% Total Votes", main = "Relationship between Star Rating and Total Votes ", col ="darkblue",lwd=1.5)

#Based on graph, we found that as the star rating increases percentage of Total votes decreases or reviews with 1 star rating have more percentage of Total votes than reviews with 5 star rating.

#TEXT MINING

#Build a corpus and make data uitable for text mining
review_Corpus <- Corpus(VectorSource(review_body)) 
#review_Corpus<-sample(review_Corpus, 500000)


#Converting reviews to lower text
review_clean<-tm_map(review_Corpus,tolower)
## Warning in tm_map.SimpleCorpus(review_Corpus, tolower): transformation
## drops documents
#Remove Punctuation marks
review_clean<-tm_map(review_clean,removePunctuation) 
## Warning in tm_map.SimpleCorpus(review_clean, removePunctuation):
## transformation drops documents
#Remove all unwanted numbers
review_clean<-tm_map(review_clean,removeNumbers)
## Warning in tm_map.SimpleCorpus(review_clean, removeNumbers): transformation
## drops documents
#Remove Stop Words
review_clean<-tm_map(review_clean,removeWords, stopwords("english"))
## Warning in tm_map.SimpleCorpus(review_clean, removeWords,
## stopwords("english")): transformation drops documents
#Remove White spaces
review_clean<-tm_map(review_clean,stripWhitespace) 
## Warning in tm_map.SimpleCorpus(review_clean, stripWhitespace):
## transformation drops documents
#review_clean$new <- seq(1:499999) check f works
#summary(review_clean)
class(review_clean)
## [1] "SimpleCorpus" "Corpus"
review_clean
## <<SimpleCorpus>>
## Metadata:  corpus specific: 1, document level (indexed): 0
## Content:  documents: 499999
#Clearing variables that are not used further.
rm(review_Corpus)

#BUILD DOCUMENT TERM MATRIX
dtm<-DocumentTermMatrix(review_clean)

## <<DocumentTermMatrix (documents: 499999, terms: 138478)>>
## Non-/sparse entries: 8569883/69230291639
## Sparsity           : 100%
## Maximal term length: 167
## Weighting          : term frequency (tf)
#Remove Sparse Terms
dtm <- removeSparseTerms(dtm, 0.99)
dtm.mat <- as.matrix(dtm)

#Convert dtm to Dataframe

#Build model using NAIVE BAYES Algoorithm

convert_count_to_boolean <- function(x) {
  y <- ifelse(x > 0, 1,0)
  y <- factor(y, levels=c(0,1), labels=c("No", "Yes"))
  y
}
